architecture-66","page_id":"architecture","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/architecture#public-functions","content":"Paginated window filtered to one view tag. Same bounds as `get_announcements`: scans only `start..min(start+limit, count)`, with the `saturating_add` clamp."},"69":{"id":"architecture-67","page_id":"architecture","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/architecture#public-functions","content":"`get_announcement_count() -> u64`"},"70":{"id":"architecture-68","page_id":"architecture","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/architecture#public-functions","content":"read"},"71":{"id":"architecture-69","page_id":"architecture","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/architecture#public-functions","content":"Total announcements; a cheap freshness check."},"72":{"id":"architecture-70","page_id":"architecture","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/architecture#storage-layout","content":"Storage is keyed, never a growing list, so a deposit's cost does **not** scale with history:"},"73":{"id":"architecture-71","page_id":"architecture","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/architecture#storage-layout","content":"Key"},"74":{"id":"architecture-72","page_id":"architecture","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/architecture#storage-layout","content":"Value"},"75":{"id":"architecture-73","page_id":"architecture","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/architecture#storage-layout","content":"Purpose"},"76":{"id":"architecture-74","page_id":"architecture","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/architecture#storage-layout","content":"`Balance(stealth_pk, token)`"},"77":{"id":"architecture-75","page_id":"architecture","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/architecture#storage-layout","content":"`i128`"},"78":{"id":"architecture-76","page_id":"architecture","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/architecture#storage-layout","content":"Per-(key, token) balance. Not a mixer: each stealth key has its own isolated balance."},"79":{"id":"architecture-77","page_id":"architecture","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/architecture#storage-layout","content":"`Nonce(stealth_pk)`"},"80":{"id":"architecture-78","page_id":"architecture","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/architecture#storage-layout","content":"`u64`"},"81":{"id":"architecture-79","page_id":"architecture","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/architecture#storage-layout","content":"Replay protection; must strictly increase."},"82":{"id":"architecture-80","page_id":"architecture","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/architecture#storage-layout","content":"`Announcement(index)`"},"83":{"id":"architecture-81","page_id":"architecture","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/architecture#storage-layout","content":"`AnnouncementEntry`"},"84":{"id":"architecture-82","page_id":"architecture","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/architecture#storage-layout","content":"One announcement per own keyed entry: **O(1) append**, no history rewrite."},"85":{"id":"architecture-83","page_id":"architecture","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/architecture#storage-layout","content":"`AnnouncementCount`"},"86":{"id":"architecture-84","page_id":"architecture","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/architecture#storage-layout","content":"`u64`"},"87":{"id":"architecture-85","page_id":"architecture","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/architecture#storage-layout","content":"Total announcements; also the next index."},"88":{"id":"architecture-86","page_id":"architecture","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/architecture#storage-layout","content":"All entries are **persistent** storage. TTLs are extended on write and, notably, **on read**: `get_balance` and `get_nonce` bump a live entry's TTL back up to the ceiling. That means a passively-scanning recipient keeps their own balance alive without ever writing."},"89":{"id":"architecture-87","page_id":"architecture","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/architecture#authorization-model","content":"Two different mechanisms, deliberately:"},"90":{"id":"architecture-88","page_id":"architecture","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/architecture#authorization-model","content":"**`deposit`** uses `sender.require_auth()`. The sender is a normal Stellar account, so standard Soroban auth applies."},"91":{"id":"architecture-89","page_id":"architecture","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/architecture#authorization-model","content":"**`withdraw`*&#x2A; uses &#x2A;*`env.crypto().ed25519_verify`** on an explicit message, *not* `require_auth`. A stealth key is not a Stellar account and has no auth entry, so the contract verifies a raw signature instead. This is what lets **anyone** (a relayer, a friend, a fee-payer) submit the transaction on the recipient's behalf without being the recipient."},"92":{"id":"architecture-90","page_id":"architecture","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/architecture#the-withdraw-message","content":"The signed message must be byte-identical between Rust and TypeScript, a fixed **278-byte** preimage:"},"93":{"id":"architecture-91","page_id":"architecture","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/architecture#the-withdraw-message","content":"The leading 22-byte ASCII **domain tag** `SHADE-POOL-WITHDRAW-V1` (SH-3) separates a withdraw preimage from any other message a stealth key might sign. The trailing **contract address** and **network id** (= `SHA-256(network passphrase)`, matching the on-chain `env.ledger().network_id()`) bind the signature to a single deployment on a single network, preventing cross-deployment and cross-network replay."},"94":{"id":"architecture-92","page_id":"architecture","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/architecture#reentrancy-safety","content":"`withdraw` follows **checks-effects-interactions**: the nonce and balance are committed to storage **before** the external SAC `transfer` call, so a malicious token contract cannot re-enter and replay the withdrawal."},"95":{"id":"architecture-93","page_id":"architecture","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/architecture#stellar-asset-contract-sac","content":"The contract moves value through the standard token interface (`soroban_sdk::token::Client`), so it works with any **Stellar Asset Contract** (native XLM, USDC, any issued asset). Cross-contract calls are limited to these SAC `transfer` calls:"},"96":{"id":"architecture-94","page_id":"architecture","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/architecture#stellar-asset-contract-sac","content":"`deposit` → `transfer(sender → contract)`"},"97":{"id":"architecture-95","page_id":"architecture","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/architecture#stellar-asset-contract-sac","content":"`withdraw` → `transfer(contract → destination)`"},"98":{"id":"architecture-96","page_id":"architecture","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/architecture#stellar-asset-contract-sac","content":"The SDK resolves an asset string to its SAC address with `resolveTokenAddress`, and `labelForToken` reverses the deterministic native-XLM SAC id back to the label `XLM` for display."},"99":{"id":"architecture-97","page_id":"architecture","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/architecture#data-flow-pool-send--scan--claim","content":"**1. Send** (`PoolAdapter.send`)"},"100":{"id":"architecture-98","page_id":"architecture","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/architecture#data-flow-pool-send--scan--claim","content":"Decode the meta-address → `(K_spend, K_view)`"},"101":{"id":"architecture-99","page_id":"architecture","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/architecture#data-flow-pool-send--scan--claim","content":"Draw a random 32-byte ephemeral `r`; derive `P`, `R`, `view_tag`"},"102":{"id":"architecture-100","page_id":"architecture","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/architecture#data-flow-pool-send--scan--claim","content":"Resolve the asset to a SAC address; convert the amount to stroops"},"103":{"id":"architecture-101","page_id":"architecture","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/architecture#data-flow-pool-send--scan--claim","content":"Build the `deposit(...)` invocation, `prepareTransaction`, sign (local secret or external signer), submit"},"104":{"id":"architecture-102","page_id":"architecture","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/architecture#data-flow-pool-send--scan--claim","content":"Interpret the RPC result: only `SUCCESS` / `PENDING` / `DUPLICATE` count as landed; anything else throws (a `TRY_AGAIN_LATER` becomes a retryable error rather than a false success)"},"105":{"id":"architecture-103","page_id":"architecture","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/architecture#data-flow-pool-send--scan--claim","content":"**2. Scan** (`PoolAdapter.scan`)"},"106":{"id":"architecture-104","page_id":"architecture","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/architecture#data-flow-pool-send--scan--claim","content":"Read `get_announcement_count()`, a cheap freshness check that lets a caller skip a full scan"},"107":{"id":"architecture-105","page_id":"architecture","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/architecture#data-flow-pool-send--scan--claim","content":"Page `get_announcements(start, limit)` from the cursor (200 per page)"},"108":{"id":"architecture-106","page_id":"architecture","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/architecture#data-flow-pool-send--scan--claim","content":"Run the two-pass scan: ECDH + view-tag filter, then full derivation on tag matches"},"109":{"id":"architecture-107","page_id":"architecture","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/architecture#data-flow-pool-send--scan--claim","content":"For each match, read `get_balance` and drop zero balances"},"110":{"id":"architecture-108","page_id":"architecture","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/architecture#data-flow-pool-send--scan--claim","content":"Return payments plus an advanced cursor (the announcement index)"},"111":{"id":"architecture-109","page_id":"architecture","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/architecture#data-flow-pool-send--scan--claim","content":"**3. Claim / withdraw** (`PoolAdapter.withdraw`)"},"112":{"id":"architecture-110","page_id":"architecture","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/architecture#data-flow-pool-send--scan--claim","content":"Find the announcement matching the stealth address"},"113":{"id":"architecture-111","page_id":"architecture","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/architecture#data-flow-pool-send--scan--claim","content":"`recoverStealthPrivateKey` → the raw stealth scalar"},"114":{"id":"architecture-112","page_id":"architecture","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/architecture#data-flow-pool-send--scan--claim","content":"Read `get_balance` and `get_nonce`; the new nonce is `current + 1`"},"115":{"id":"architecture-113","page_id":"architecture","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/architecture#data-flow-pool-send--scan--claim","content":"Build the withdraw message; sign it with `signWithStealthKey`"},"116":{"id":"architecture-114","page_id":"architecture","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/architecture#data-flow-pool-send--scan--claim","content":"Build the `withdraw(...)` invocation sourced by the **fee payer**"},"117":{"id":"architecture-115","page_id":"architecture","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/architecture#data-flow-pool-send--scan--claim","content":"**Restore-aware prepare** (below)"},"118":{"id":"architecture-116","page_id":"architecture","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/architecture#data-flow-pool-send--scan--claim","content":"Sign the fee-payer leg; submit directly to RPC, or POST to the relayer's `/relay` for a fee-bump"},"119":{"id":"architecture-117","page_id":"architecture","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/architecture#restore-aware-preparation","content":"`server.prepareTransaction` only throws on a simulation *error*; it ignores `sim.restorePreamble`. If the recipient's `Balance`/`Nonce` entry has archived, a bare prepare would assemble the withdraw over an archived footprint: it submits, fails on-chain, and `get_balance` still shows the funds, an opaque brick."},"120":{"id":"architecture-118","page_id":"architecture","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/architecture#restore-aware-preparation","content":"`prepareWithRestore` (`packages/sdk/src/methods/restore.ts`) fixes this in three steps. On `isSimulationRestore` it builds and submits a `RestoreFootprintOp` from the preamble, then waits for it to land. Because that restore consumes the fee payer's next sequence number, it then **re-fetches the account and rebuilds the invocation on the fresh sequence**. Only then does it re-simulate. Without the rebuild, the withdraw would collide at an already-consumed sequence (`txBAD_SEQ`)."},"121":{"id":"architecture-119","page_id":"architecture","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/architecture#data-flow-account-method","content":"The `account` method never touches the contract:"},"122":{"id":"architecture-120","page_id":"architecture","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/architecture#data-flow-account-method","content":"**Send:** a classic transaction with the ephemeral `R` in a 32-byte `MemoHash`. Native XLM lands via `CreateAccount`/`Payment`; a token lands as a `CreateClaimableBalance` naming the stealth address as claimant."},"123":{"id":"architecture-121","page_id":"architecture","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/architecture#data-flow-account-method","content":"**Scan:** page Horizon transactions; for each hash-memo tx, decode the memo as a candidate `R`, derive the stealth address, and look for an operation whose destination matches. The destination match **is** the verification, no view tag needed. With an indexer configured, the covered span of that walk consumes the indexer's pre-extracted candidate feed instead (operations inlined, no per-tx round-trip), and a Horizon tail always runs last."},"124":{"id":"architecture-122","page_id":"architecture","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/architecture#data-flow-account-method","content":"**Claim:** sign with the recovered stealth key: `AccountMerge` (full sweep) or `Payment` (partial) for XLM; `ChangeTrust` + `ClaimClaimableBalance` (+ optional exit) for a token, or a relayer-sponsored claim."},"125":{"id":"architecture-123","page_id":"architecture","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/architecture#the-announcement-indexer","content":"The `account` method publishes **no view tag**: the transaction's `MemoHash` *is* the ephemeral key `R`. Every hash-memo transaction on the network is therefore a discovery candidate, and the original scan walked the **global Horizon transaction feed client-side**: minutes for a cold scan on testnet, unbounded as a network grows."},"126":{"id":"architecture-124","page_id":"architecture","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/architecture#the-announcement-indexer","content":"The **announcement indexer** (`packages/indexer`, a standalone service like the relayer) moves that walk server-side, **once for everyone**. It polls Horizon `/transactions?order=asc`, keeps **only** successful hash-memo transactions (their operation records stored **verbatim**) and serves them as a compact candidate feed the client filters **locally**. There is deliberately **no address- or R-keyed query**: any such query would let the operator link your keys to your requests."},"127":{"id":"architecture-125","page_id":"architecture","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/architecture#trust-model","content":"**An indexer can *hide* payments; it cannot *fabricate* them.** A candidate only becomes \"your payment\" after the client itself derives the stealth address from `R`, and everything is re-verified on-chain at claim time. The indexer is an **availability optimization**; **Horizon remains the source of truth**:"},"128":{"id":"architecture-126","page_id":"architecture","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/architecture#trust-model","content":"The scan probes the indexer's `/health` first and silently stays on the pure Horizon walk when the indexer is unreachable, unhealthy (any degraded coverage state, see below), on the wrong network, or self-reporting more lag than `ClientConfig.indexerMaxLagSeconds` (default 6 h; an operationally abandoned indexer is not worth electing)."},"129":{"id":"architecture-127","page_id":"architecture","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/architecture#trust-model","content":"Every scan **finishes with a Horizon tail** from the final cursor, so indexer lag cannot hide a payment."},"130":{"id":"architecture-128","page_id":"architecture","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/architecture#trust-model","content":"An indexer fault **mid-scan** degrades automatically to the Horizon walk from the last good cursor."},"131":{"id":"architecture-129","page_id":"architecture","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/architecture#trust-model","content":"After the covered span, the scan **re-checks `/health` once more**: a gap the indexer recorded *while the scan was consuming its feed* discards the segment's results, and the tail re-walks the whole span, so a mid-scan hole can never advance the client cursor past a payment."},"132":{"id":"architecture-130","page_id":"architecture","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/architecture#trust-model","content":"The persisted cursor is **clamped to the head the client's own Horizon reports** whenever the tail saw nothing: one malicious far-future cursor cannot blind future scans (they would otherwise resume beyond the chain head and find nothing, forever)."},"133":{"id":"architecture-131","page_id":"architecture","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/architecture#trust-model","content":"Cursors are Horizon `paging_token`s, so indexer and Horizon cursors are **interchangeable in both directions**."},"134":{"id":"architecture-132","page_id":"architecture","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/architecture#cold-scans-and-coverage","content":"With no saved cursor and a healthy indexer, a scan **fast-starts at the indexer's coverage start** (`startCursor` from `/health`) instead of genesis. The trade-off: a payment predating the indexer's coverage is found only by the **exhaustive walk** (CLI `--full-rescan`, SDK `ScanOpts.exhaustive`), which walks the pre-indexer prefix on Horizon from genesis (the indexer still serves the covered span)."},"135":{"id":"architecture-133","page_id":"architecture","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/architecture#coverage-honesty","content":"A coverage claim is only useful if the indexer **owns its failures**. The ingester runs a periodic **feed continuity check** against Horizon's retention bounds, and because a recorded gap is *permanent*, the check fails **closed** in every direction: ingestion never starts before the process's first successful check (a cold start against a broken root document must not silently cross a retention hole); bounds from a root document reporting a different network passphrase are discarded (a mistyped `HORIZON_URL` cannot poison the gap store); and a hole (starting at the cursor ledger itself, whose tail may be partially unserved) is recorded only after **two consecutive observations**, with paging paused in between."},"136":{"id":"architecture-134","page_id":"architecture","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/architecture#coverage-honesty","content":"Every failure mode degrades `/health` (`status: 'degraded'`, each cause exposed individually): a recorded **gap**, a **suspected testnet reset** (cursor impossibly far past the chain head, confirmed twice and then *latched* until restart, so a stale-era database never becomes trustworthy again just because the new chain outgrows it), a **persistently failing continuity check** (`continuityStale`: gap/reset detection is effectively off, so coverage cannot be vouched for), and a **stalled ingest loop** (`stalled`: a frozen indexer must not report `ok` forever). SDK guards require `status: 'ok'`, so every degraded state routes clients back to Horizon automatically. A hole can never *hide* a payment, it only costs speed."},"137":{"id":"architecture-135","page_id":"architecture","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/architecture#endpoints","content":"Endpoint"},"138":{"id":"architecture-136","page_id":"architecture","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/architecture#endpoints","content":"What it returns"},"139":{"id":"architecture-137","page_id":"architecture","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/architecture#endpoints","content":"`GET /health`"},"140":{"id":"architecture-138","page_id":"architecture","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/architecture#endpoints","content":"`status` (`ok`\\|`degraded`, see Coverage honesty), `network`, `store` (`postgres`\\|`memory`), `cursor`, `startCursor`, `lastCloseTime`, `lagSeconds`, `announcements` (count), recorded feed `gaps` (always present, `[]` when none), `ingest` (`lastPollAt`, `lastError`, `resetSuspected`, `lastContinuityOkAt`, `continuityStale`, `stalled`)"},"141":{"id":"architecture-139","page_id":"architecture","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/architecture#endpoints","content":"`GET /announcements?cursor=&limit=`"},"142":{"id":"architecture-140","page_id":"architecture","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/architecture#endpoints","content":"Hash-memo candidate records (Horizon transaction shape, `operations` inlined verbatim, plus the transaction's `source_account`; rows ingested before the field existed omit it) strictly after `cursor`; `limit` capped at 200. The response `cursor` resumes paging, jumping to the indexer's global position once the feed is drained"},"143":{"id":"architecture-141","page_id":"architecture","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/architecture#endpoints","content":"Both endpoints are rate limited per client IP: `429` with a `Retry-After` reporting the real remaining wait. The SDK treats a `429` as a fault (Horizon fallback), so the `/announcements` default is generous."},"144":{"id":"architecture-142","page_id":"architecture","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/architecture#configuration","content":"All configuration is environment variables. `packages/indexer/.env.example` is the annotated list:"},"145":{"id":"architecture-143","page_id":"architecture","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/architecture#configuration","content":"Variable"},"14